[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]18.
[normal] 
[normal]In Bedfordshire, in addition to plans for 80 new officers, the PCC has been working to deliver more policing volunteers and greater diversity in the force.  Volunteer applications from people from black and minority ethnic (BME) backgrounds have gone up by a third since last November
[normal].
[normal] 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]19.
[normal] 
[normal]In Sussex, the PCC opened recruitment for 80 new police constables and 30 PCSOs. 
[normal] 
[normal]In addition, 32 civilian response investigator roles have been created in order to release warranted officers onto the front line.  The PCC has also set out her plans to recruit 120 new Specials in 2014, 
[normal]while in Devon and Cornwall there are plans for 200 extra Specials.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]20.
[normal] 
[normal]PCCs are visible and are engaging with the public, they are driving innovation and they are prioritising front line policing to ensure effective policing in each force area.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The role of commissioners in holding their chief constables to account;[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]21.
[normal] 
[normal]Section 17 of the 
[normal]Policing 
[normal]Protoc
[normal]o
[normal]l
[normal] Order 2011
[normal] sets out the powers and duties held by PCCs to hold their Chief Constable to account.
[normal] T
[normal]he relationship between the PCC and their Chief Constable should be constructive, but that does not mean they should always agree. Indeed, in holding Chiefs to account PCCs
[normal] 
[normal]must
[normal] challenge, question and probe.
[normal] 
[normal]T
[normal]he Protocol sets out
[normal] that public accountability for the delivery and performance of policing is passed to the PCC 
[normal]on behalf of the electorate
[normal]. The PCC is accountable to the electorate, the Chief Constable to the PCC.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]22.
[normal] 
[normal]There are many examples of PCCs 
[normal]publically and robustly holding their Chief Constables to account
[normal]. For instance
[normal],
[normal] 
[normal]in February 2013
[normal], Kent PCC 
[normal]Ann Barnes, 
[normal]c
[normal]all
[normal]ed
[normal] in HMIC 
[normal]over her
[normal] 
[normal]concern
[normal]s
[normal] 
[normal]about
[normal] 
[normal]police crime recording. 
[normal]The 
[normal]resulting 
[normal]report, published in June
[normal],
[normal] showed that “
[normal]appreciably more
[normal]” needed to be done to ensure the people of Kent could have confidence in their recorded crime figures. The PCC 
[normal]was outspoken following the findings of the report and challenged her force to improve, 
[normal]and 
[normal]Ms Barnes has invited HMIC back to Kent to follow up their June report and indicate what progress has been made.
[normal] 
[normal]This demonstrates the power 
[normal]and level of scrutiny 
[normal]a PCC can bring to bear on matters of absolutely central importance to issues such as confidence in the local police force.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]23.
[normal] 
[normal]This Committee has previously looked at the powers of PCCs to remove their Chief Constables
[normal] and the
[normal] Government ha
[normal]s
[normal] recently responded to that report.
[normal] We have made clear that
[normal] there are appropriate safeguards in place regarding the removal of Chief Constables, and that the Police and Crime Panels who scrutinise these decisions have the appropriate powers.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]24.
[normal] 
[normal]U
[normal]ltimately
[normal],
[normal] 
[normal]PCCs
[normal] are public bodies
[normal].  I
[normal]n exercising all their powers they must act reasonably and proportionately
[normal],
[normal] and 
[normal]they 
[normal]benefit from statutory monitoring officers to advise them on these legal issues. As Her Majesty’s Chief Inspector recently stated in a speech on this issue: 
[normal]The statutory scheme of local accountability established in the Police Reform and Social Responsibility Act 2011 is, on its face and, I believe, in its substance, a coherent and rational one.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]25.
[normal] 
[normal]It is for Police and Crime Panels, 
[normal]the public and
[normal],
[normal] if needed
[normal],
[normal] the Courts
[normal],
[normal] to decide 
[normal]whether the
[normal] powers of dismissal 
[normal]have been used appropriately
[normal]. 
[normal] 
[normal]It is right that t
[normal]he 
[normal]ability 
[normal]to appoint and to fire Chief Constables
[normal] 
[normal]is defined
[normal] in statute and exercised by the individual elected by the public to hold the Chief Constable to account
[normal]. Th
[normal]e
[normal] power
[normal],
[normal] and the willingness of PCCs to consider its use, forms a crucial element of how PCCs can hold their Chiefs to account
[normal].
[normal] 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]26.
[normal] 
[normal]There are many examples
[normal], un
[normal]reported in the national media
[normal],
[normal] of 
[normal]how 
[normal]PCCs 
[normal]are 
[normal]holding Chiefs to account
[normal] locally
[normal]. For instance in Hampshire
[normal], Simon
[normal] Hayes holds 
[normal]a series of 
[normal]‘
[normal]COMPASS 
[normal]meetings
[normal]’
[normal] 
[normal](Commissioner’s Performance, Accountability, Scrutiny and Strategy meeting)
[normal]. These
[normal] 
[normal]bi-monthly meetings 
[normal]have cover
[normal]ed
[normal] a wide range of topics, 
[normal]with 
[normal]m
[normal]embers of the public invited to submit questions
[normal].
[normal] 
[normal]F
[normal]rom December
[normal],
[normal] these will be public events held at various locations throughout the area to allow as many people as possible to attend
[normal].
[normal] 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]27.
[normal] 
[normal]Along similar line
[normal]s,
[normal] 
[normal]the
[normal] 
[normal]Sussex PCC ha
[normal]s started to
[normal] 
[normal]stream
[normal] meetings, such as 
[normal]her monthly 
[normal]Performance and Accountability meetings
[normal] with the Chief Constable
