[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]29.
[normal] 
[normal]PCCs have a clearly defined role in holding their Chief Constable to account, and there is strong evidence that they are taking this role seriously.
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]The role of police and crime panels in holding their commissioners to account;[bold]&#xa0;[bold]30.
[normal] 
[normal]Police and crime panels (PCPs) perform a scrutiny function for PCCs, providing both support and challenge to PCCs on the exercise of their functions, and acting as a critical friend.
[normal] 
[normal]As set out in the Policing Protocol Order 2011, the role of the Panel as underpinned in the Police Reform and Social Responsibility Act is to 
[normal]provide: 
[normal]checks and balances in relation to the performance of the PCC. The Panel does not scrutinise the Chief Constable – it scrutinises the PCC‘s exercise of their statutory functions
[normal]. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]31.
[normal] 
[normal]The roles and responsibilities of th
[normal]o
[normal]se 
[normal]in the new policing landscape are not only set out clearly in the Act
[normal] and
[normal] in the Protocol but also 
[normal]in the Accountability System Statement for Policing and Crime Reduction.
[normal] This document also sets out other key responsibilities within the system, such as the role of the Home Office.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]32.
[normal] 
[normal]Panels focus their attention on key strategic actions and decisions taken by the Commissioner including whether they have achieved the objectives set out in their Police and Crime Plan and Annual Report, and consulted appropriately with the public.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]33.
[normal] 
[normal]Transparency 
[normal]is 
[normal]key. Panels meet in public to ensur
[normal]e
[normal] information is available to the electorate so that they can hold their respective PCCs to account for their decisions. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]34.
[normal] 
[normal]The Home Office is confident that PCPs have the powers they need to hold Commissioners to account. 
[normal]The powers and responsibilities of PCPs are set out in sections 28 to 30 and 32 to 33 of the Police Reform and Social Responsibility Act 2011, and there is further relevant provision in Schedules 1, 3, 5, 7 and 8 to the Act.
[normal] 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]35.
[normal] 
[normal]PCPs also have the power to veto (with a two-thirds majority) the PCC’s proposed policing precept and the appointment of a chief constable.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]36.
[normal] 
[normal]T
[normal]he Home Office produced guidance setting out all of the 
[normal]s
[normal]econdary 
[normal]l
[normal]egislation 
[normal]that applies to PCPs and has issued guidance to sit alongside that legislation.
[normal] The Local Government Association, in Association with the Centre for Public Scrutiny, have also produced guidance on the role and composition of PCPs.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]37.
[normal] 
[normal]The Panels have an important role to play in this process, and their powers are
[normal] well defined and
[normal] significant. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The division of functions and staff between commissioners and chief constables following the Stage 2 transfers under the Police Reform and Social Responsibility Act 2011;[bold]&#xa0;[bold]38.
[normal] 
[normal]Government’s 
[normal]intention has always been to give as much flexibility locally as possible. We have not wanted to unnecessarily influence or undermine local discussions and
[normal],
[normal] as such
[normal],
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]the Government has been consistent in our view that initial plans for staff transfers under Stage 2 were decisions for PCCs and Chiefs to take locally. 
[normal]To assist PCCs and Chiefs in drawing up these plans we 
[normal]set
[normal] out three key principles 
[normal]and reiterated the policy intention behind stage 2.
[normal] 
[normal]The 
[normal]three principles 
[normal]we set out were
[normal]:
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]39.
[normal] 
[normal]We also specified that 
[normal]Stage 2 
[normal]plans should not jeopardise the implementation of the policing plan, or the strategic duties of the force. We were clear that the intention of the Government and of Parliament in making the Chief Constable an employer – which was that operational staff, as a minimum, should transfer to 
[normal]the Chief Constable – is a key consideration and one which Stage 2 plans needed to take into account. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]40.
[normal] 
[normal]We are clear that, within the parameters set out by the above principles, it is right to offer PCCs and Chiefs the local flexibility to organise their staffing arrangements to best meet their local needs. Stage 2 plans have now been submitted and considered by the trade union organisations. As of 9 December 2013, the Home Secretary has approved the 
[normal]majority of 
[normal]plans from PCCs and 
[normal]the Department is
[normal] in the process of reviewing the remainder. There is sufficient time to ensure that all transition plans will be in place in time for a smooth transfer of staff in time for the next financial year. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]41.
[normal] 
[normal]We have set out that an integrated Scheme of Governance should be prepared by the PCC, in consultation with the Chief Constable. The revised Financial Management Code of Practice provides clarity around the financial governance arrangements within the police in England and Wales. It sets out specifically the key elements of what should be included in an integrated Scheme. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]42.
[normal] 
[normal]The Stage 2 staff transfer scheme acknowledges the important divide between operat
[normal]ional policing and the role of
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]the PCC, whilst also allowing for variation to meet local needs. 
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]The role of commissioners in budget and precept setting;[bold]&#xa0;[bold]43.
[normal] 
[normal]The Home Secretary has protected the police from further Departmental budget reductions during the 2010 Spending Review period. In addition to excluding the police from any reductions relating to the 2011 announcement on pay restraint the Government decided to also protect the police from reductions announced to the Home Office budget in the Autumn Statement 2012. The Home Office is currently considering the implications of the latest Autumn Statement for the police alongside all Home Office budgets in the round. However, there is no question that the police will still have the resources to do their important work.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]44.
[normal] 
[normal]These are, undoubtedly, tough economic times, but over the past three years we have seen forces rising to the challenge and meeting local community needs and cutting crime whilst managing these difficult budgetary issues. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]45.
[normal] 
[normal]PCCs have a vital role to play in this area but, again, it is not for 
[normal]Government 
[normal]to assess their relative success. HMIC review the success of forces and it is their 
[normal]Policing in Austerity 
[normal]report (July 2013)
[normal] 
[normal]that provides the evidence that forces are 
[normal]rising to the challenge
[normal] 
[normal]and have plans in place to meet the financial challenge. The Report found that police forces are delivering savings whilst maintaining and improving services for the public: crime is falling; the proportion of officers on the 
[normal]frontline is increasing 
[normal](from 88.9% in March 2010 to 90.6% in March 2013) 
[normal]and victim satisfaction is up
[normal] (84.6% of victims were satisfied with their overall experience in March 2013, compared to 82.2% in March 2010)
[normal].  
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]46.
[normal] 
[normal]PCCs are driving efficiencies across their forces. We have seen PCCs exploring partnerships with private companies, and focusing on better use of technology. In some instances we have seen old and costly 
[normal]buildings
[normal] being 
[normal]vacated
[normal] 
[normal]in favour of co-locati
[normal]on between
[normal] local fire services,
[normal] police forces and/ or L
[normal]ocal Government,
[normal] leading to a more effective, joined up, and efficient service.
[normal] The HMIC Report shows there are opportunities to go even further through greater collaboration and improved digital working. The Government is supporting the police to do this, including by creating a £50 million
[normal] a year
[normal] 
[normal]innovation fund 
[normal]from 2014/15 as well as a precursor fund of 
[normal]£20 million this year to
[normal] enable them to press ahead with transformation in their forces.
[normal] 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]47.
[normal] 
[normal]PCCs are driving efficiencies locally to 
[normal]maintain effective policing.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The effectiveness of commissioners in promoting local policing priorities;[bold]&#xa0;[bold]48.
[normal] 
[normal]Promoting local policing needs is a central function of a PCC
[normal]. PCCs are locally accountable, they have a duty to consult when drafting the Police and Crime Plan for their local area, including consulting victims of crime. 
[normal]Reviewing the Police and Crime Plans highlights many common issues that affect communities throughout England and Wales, but many of these issues present differently in different locations
[normal], from sparsely populated 
[normal]rural communities to demographically diverse urban areas
[normal]. 
[normal]The role of PCCs is to ensure that the needs of their local communities are met
[normal].
[normal] 
[normal]PCCs are engag
[normal]ing
[normal] 
[normal]in innovative ways 
[normal]with their communities
[normal] to identify and promote
[normal] local priorities. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]49.
[normal] 
[normal]A number of PCCs have driven forward initiatives to tackle rural crime.  North Wales PCC 
[normal]Winston 
[normal]Roddick
[normal] has 
[normal]established a plan that
[normal] includes a Rural Crime Team of officers, police community support officers (PCSOs) and special constables
[normal]. The teams
[normal] provide a vital link between rural communit
[normal]ies and North 
[normal]Wales Police, focu
[normal]sing
[normal] on issues such as theft of farming equipment and livestock. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]50.
[normal] 
[normal]In Suffolk, the PCC has introduced a dedicated team of Special Constables to work with Safer Neighbourhoods teams to tackle offenders who target farms and rural communities, as well as rural crime police officers who will focus on hare coursing.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]51.
[normal] 
[normal]Thames Valley PCC
[normal],
[normal] Anthony Stansfeld
[normal],
[normal] has also prioritised rural crime, with the introduction of the ‘Country Watch’ messaging system.  So far over 7,500 people have signed up to the system to receive crime alerts, witness appeals, galleries of wanted criminals or suspects, information on community groups, events or meetings and details of operational or proactive work going on in their area by email, text or telephone. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]52.
[normal] 
[normal]In Staffordshire, the PCC has 
[normal]introduced
[normal] 
[normal]‘Cars Behind Bars’ to address the problem of uninsured motorists across Staffordshire and Stoke-on-Trent.  The 
[normal]scheme uses automatic number plate recognition to identify uninsured vehicles, with over 700 vehicles seized in four months.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]53.
[normal] 
[normal]PCCs are also addressing some of the challenges of policing in urban areas, including addressing the challenges posed by a vibrant night-time economy.  
[normal]In Northumbria, following the rape of a teenage girl, the PCC worked with partners to introduce vulnerability awareness training for all door staff working in the night time economy.  This 
[normal]has been 
[normal]incorporated into the current mandatory Security Industry Authority developed training modules for door supervisors
[normal] and is being delivered nationwide
[normal].
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]54.
[normal] 
[normal]In Merseyside, Jane Kennedy has worked to increase the diversity of Merseyside Police, with a positive action Leadership Programme aimed at increasing recruitment of under-represented groups to the special constabulary and regular police force
[normal].
[normal] 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]55.
[normal] 
[normal]Ensuring forces concentrate on local priorities is a 
[normal]key
[normal] challenge for PCCs
[normal] 
[normal]an
[normal]d those who do not sufficiently tackle local issues 
[normal]will
[normal] 
[normal]be held to account at the ballot box.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Progress on establishing collaboration agreements with other commissioners, policing organisations and partners; [bold]&#xa0;
[normal]56.
[normal] 
[normal]Section 10 of t
[normal]he Police Reform and Social Responsibility Act 2011 placed a new duty on Police and Crime Commissioners and Chief Constables to collaborate where it is in the interests of efficiency and effectiveness.
[normal] 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]57.
[normal] 
[normal]C
[normal]hief Constables are also under a duty to have regard to the Strategic Policing Requirement, which 
[normal]sets out in statute the need for collective capabilities to meet national threats. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]58.
[normal] 
[normal]PCCs are taking this task seriously and 
[normal]in their July 2013 publication 
[normal]Policing in Austerity: Rising to the Challenge
[normal], HMIC said that “
[normal]Following their election in November 2012, many PCCs have galvanised the agenda in their area or region, providing fresh impetus to collaboration
[normal].”
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]59.
[normal] 
[normal]Warwickshire and 
[normal]West Mercia represent a good example
[normal] of 
[normal]where the PCCs are playing an important part in leading 
[normal]collaboration
[normal] and ensuring momentum is maintained, all with the aim of ensuring savings are made and more resources are focused on the frontline
[normal].
[normal] This 
[normal]important
[normal] initiative, through which
[normal] functions below Deputy Chief Constable in
[normal] 
[normal]Warwickshire and West Mercia are now joint ones for the two forces
[normal],
[normal] has achieved significant savings. According to 
[normal]HMIC
[normal], this alliance will allow 
[normal]Warwickshire and West Mercia
[normal] 
[normal]to achieve 75 per cent and 94 per cent of their respective Spending Review savings by 2014/15.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]60.
[normal] 
[normal]PCCs in the East Midlands (Derbyshire, Leicestershire, Lincolnshire, Northamptonshire and Nottinghamshire) commissioned HMIC to conduct a review of their collaboration arrangements, which reported in October 2013. This commission demonstrates the willingness of PCCs to apply a high level of scrutiny and challenge ensuring value for money is achieved.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]61.
[normal] 
[normal]In stark contrast to 
[normal]police authorities
[normal],
[normal] 
[normal]PCCs are 
[normal]already 
[normal]looking 
[normal]beyond the traditional options for reform 
[normal]and 
[normal]exploring what more ambitious, innovative and transformational options exist to make savings and improve services. Many are turning their attention to those outside the immediate policing family including
[normal] other emergency services.  There is already innovative work taking place between PCCs, fire authorities and ambulance trusts and it’s clear that where the emergency services collaborate they can deliver efficiencies.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]62.
[normal] 
[normal]In Hampshire, the fire service, police force and the county council are joining up corporate services and expect to save around £4 million a year.  In Merseyside, the PCC, Jane Kennedy, signed the contract for the building work to begin on a joint police and fire command and control centre.  Matthew Grove, the PCC in Humberside, has made clear that he wants to see long term savings delivered from emergency services collaboration and is now working with the fire authority to achieve significant savings by developing a joint vehicle and equipment workshop.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]63.
[normal] 
[normal]In Surr
[normal]ey, the PCC and Chief Constable
[normal] are leading the way with a full programme of collaboration between the police, fire and south east coast ambulance.  The collaboration will see the three services join forces to find ways of streamlining operations, sharing more premises and delivering joint safety campaigns, as well as looking to link up with Sussex’s emergency services.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]64.
[normal] 
[normal]I
[normal]n Northamptonshire, the Police and Crime Commissioner, with the support of the County Council, is 
[normal]leading work for
[normal] 
[normal]much closer collaborative working between fire and police.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]65.
[normal] 
[normal]Government supports this collaboration. As previously set out at Spending Round 2013, the Home Secretary agreed to establish a Police Innovation Fund from 2014/15 worth £50m per annum. The Police Innovation Fund has as one of its core objectives to incentivise collaboration and transformation and enable forces and PCCs to invest in innovative approaches with the potential to improve policing and deliver further efficiencies in the future. To enable PCCs to press ahead now with this transformational work, an additional £20m has been made available in this financial year as a Precursor Innovation Fund.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]66.
[normal] 
[normal]Collaboration is an important method of increasing both the efficiency and effectiveness of public services, and we have seen examples of PCCs driving this important work.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Transparency of and rep[bold]orting by commissioners to date;[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]67.
[normal] 
[normal]The Government expects high standards of transparency and has set out the information that PCCs must publish to support the public in effectively holding them to account. The requirements to publish this information are set out in the Elected Local Bodies Specified Information Order 2011.
[normal] 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]68.
[normal] 
[normal]PCCs 
[normal]are 
[normal]also 
[normal]legally required
[normal] 
[normal]to publish 
[normal]a 
[normal]register of interests, including every pecuniary interest or other paid interest; budgets; contracts and tenders; senior salaries; expenses; and key decisions.  
[normal]The role of Police and Crime Commissioner
[normal]s
[normal] is clearly set out in legislation and supporting statutory documents such as the Policing Protocol.  Expenses claimed by PCCs are reimbursement for costs incurred whilst undertaking these duties. By publically setting rates and requiring full publication of expenses quarterly the Government is ensuring PCCs will be fair and transparent in claiming expenses.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]69.
[normal] 
[normal]The local electorate will judge whether PCCs are making best use of public money and hold them to account at the ballot box.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]70.
[normal] 
[normal]The PCC must also publish an annual report which will set out performance against spending and provide the platform on which the police and crime panel can seek to challenge and support the PCC in developing their police and crime plan.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]71.
[normal] 
[normal]It is not 
[normal]t
[normal]he
[normal] Government
[normal]’s role
[normal] 
[normal]to monitor compliance.  
[normal]It is for 
[normal]the Chief Executive, 
[normal]as monitoring officer
[normal],
[normal] to ensure that the PCC has complied with all legal duties.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]72.
[normal] 
[normal]In addition t
[normal]he 
[normal]P
[normal]olice and 
[normal]C
[normal]rime 
[normal]P
[normal]anel is responsible for scrutinising the PCC
[normal]s actions,
[normal] which 
[normal]allows them to use their powers to examine 
[normal]their compliance with statutory duties.
[normal] They themselves have powers as set out in the P
[normal]olice Reform and Social Responsibility 
[normal]Act
[normal] 2011
[normal] to require information from the PCC, including requiring the PCC to attend to give evidence. 
[normal]T
[normal]he PCC as a public body is 
[normal]ultimately 
[normal]accountable to the courts for meeting their statutory duties
[normal].
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]73.
[normal] 
[normal]Of equal significance is the 
[normal]PCC
[normal]’s status
[normal] 
[normal]as an elected body,
[normal] accountable to the public at the ballot box
[normal]. A
[normal]s we have seen in a range of cases
[normal] in the last year, the 
[normal]Elected Local Bodies Specified 
[normal]Information Order 
[normal]2011 
[normal]is being used extensively by the media and the public, including this Committee to provide detailed 
[normal]scrutiny
[normal] on what PCCs are spending.  The work of this committee is testament to the scrutiny applied to the use of public money in the new policing governance model; this is in stark contrast to the invisible and opaque world of 
[normal]p
[normal]olice 
[normal]a
[normal]uthorities. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]74.
[normal] 
[normal]PCCs work in the full glare of public scrutiny, legislation clearly sets out the information they are required to publish and, ultimately PCCs can be held to account by the electorate.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Conclusion[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]75.
[normal] 
[normal]PCCs have been in place a little over 12 months. In that short time they have become increasingly visible, actively seeking to engage with the public. They have set budgets and established Police and Crime Plans. They have introduced innovative policies to tackle local problems, and have publically held their Chief Constables to account.
[normal] They have sought to introduce collaboration with other forces and with other providers, and they have driven efficiencies. 
[normal]L
[normal]ocal innovation backed by full public accountability is driving modern policing.
